Attempt at Categorizing UFO Sightings¶

Matthew Peach¶

I'm wondering if a model could categorize the shape of a reported UFO. I've come a long way since working on this dataset in an earlier project. I now know how to encode categorical data and use flair to transform text into data that is more usable. So, I'm really excited to try this out.

I'd like to use "shape" as the target, but there's a few things I don't like about this data as-is:

  • "other" is the 5th most reported shape.
  • "fireball" could easily describe a meteor.
  • A few are the shapes are very infrequently reported.

What is the difference between "text" and "summary"?¶

"summary" is a summary of "text" - the raw texts can be quite long (as shown below).

Grey Spheres flying fast, and low above city, appearing out of nowhere and disappearing into nothing. 
 
My fiancé and I stepped outside our business for a cigarette. We run an exotic animal rescue and actually live in the back, there is an apartment. We were talking and I was looking at the sky, the next I thing I see is 5 grey, metallic looking spheres flying very low above our business and off into the distance disappearing. When the spheres first appeared they where in an uneven triangle formation then all switched positions, some overlapping others( looked higher up in the sky). The whole event only look seconds and my fiancé saw a large flash in the sky afterward. I’ve gone through a few options of what they could such as drones or helicopter, they made absolutely no noise and it was extra quiet when they went by. They didn’t have any lights, and I got a clear shot from how low some dropped to when they split from the triangle formation. Some of our animals have been acting spooked, or even just on edge since the incident occurred. Which is odd because we have no windows in our unit, so they wouldn’t be able to see anything anyways. Sometimes you can tell if it’s man made, or even the government…this time I have no idea what I even saw, hence my reason for this report.

Encoding the Classes¶

This is a bit based on opinion, but I think a lot of these shapes could be condensed into one shape. I also think they could potentially be ordered based on number of sides or edges. For example, light has 0 edges, disk/circle has one, triangle, delta have 3. I also think some shapes should just be dropped for being too rare.

Here's what I've decided to do:

Drop¶

  • unknown - This is a classification task, so this is kind of useless.
  • other - Not sure what this is representative of.
  • cross - Too few and too different than the other shapes.
  • fireball - Could easily be a meteor, but why weren't these not originally classified as "light"?
  • star - Too few and is this a five-pointed shape or shaped like a star in the night sky?
  • changing - Changing what? Light color, shape, direction?



Again, these class groupings/encodings are fairly opinion-based.

Class Encodings¶

  • 0: light, flash - No associated physical shape.
  • 1: circle, disk - Circular shapes.
  • 2: sphere, oval, teardrop, egg - Ovoid shapes.
  • 3: cigar, cylinder - Elongated ovoid shapes.
  • 4: triangle, cone - Triangular shapes.
  • 5: rectangle, diamond - Rectangular shapes.
  • 6: formation, chevron, delta - Various in one sighting. This one is a bit strange since it doesn't really specify a shape of an individual object.

Encoding Date¶

In [27]:
def datetime64_to_DDMMYY(dataFrame, columnName):
    date = str(dataFrame[columnName])
    dateArr = date.replace(" ", "-").split("-")
    dataFrame["day"] = int(dateArr[2])
    dataFrame["month"] = int(dateArr[1])
    dataFrame["year"] = int(dateArr[0])
    return dataFrame

df = df.apply(lambda x: datetime64_to_DDMMYY(x, "date_time"), axis = 1)

Voting Classifier¶

I'm leaving out the SVM here because it didn't work out.

This time I'm using soft voting instead of hard voting since I don't think hard voting with only two models makes sense - wouldn't it result in a tie sometimes? From what I understand, soft voting can weigh the votes differently based on confidence.

In [42]:
%%time
from sklearn.ensemble import VotingClassifier

randomForestVoter = RandomForestClassifier(random_state = 93)
extraTreesVoter = ExtraTreesClassifier(random_state = 93)

voting_clf = VotingClassifier(
    estimators = [("Random Forest", randomForestVoter), ("Extra Trees", extraTreesVoter)],
    voting = "soft"
)

Summary¶

I'm really disappointed that this didn't work well. I may have transformed the data too much or maybe the instances just aren't very related. The SVC is the most "accurate," but that's only because it classified every instance as "lights," which was the majority of instances.
